@Wenpei Thank you for this contribution. At the top of the script, could you update the license to the Apache license?

@frreiss @mboehm7
What is the procedure to accept new algorithms? After @fmakari validates the script, can the algorithm be merged in? I am asking because some other potential steps are 1) corresponding data generation script, 2) test cases added to test suite, 3) update algorithms reference, and maybe 4) PyDML equivalent? However, requirement of any of these additional points might discourage contributions. Would scripts/staging be the place to put an algorithm contribution that is validated but does not have the additional points 1) through 3)?

@mboehm7 Yes, I meant the ./scripts/algorithms directory. Ideally it would be to nice to have a particular set of DML scripts (the ones in ./scripts/algorithms) that are all validated/tested/documented that are the gold standard. A user can be certain of the integrity of a script in ./scripts/algorithms. It 'works', it is high performance, it scales, it's easy to generate sample data, it's tested, and it's well documented.

At the same time, there is great value in encouraging algorithm writers to contribute additional algorithms without burdening them with other requirements (an R specialist shouldn't need to write any Java). Perhaps a new script can undergo an "incubation", which can involve contributions from the community (add test cases, validate performance, etc) to assist in its move to being a main algorithm.

We should make sure that our process of accepting new DML scripts: (1) maintains the integrity of existing first-tier algorithms and (2) encourages algorithm writers to contribute new scripts. This 'process' could be as simple as starting a new script in the staging directory and moving it to ./scripts/algorithms when it graduates once it meets the requirements of a first-tier algorithm. We just need to define what those requirements are so that we maintain the integrity of the first-tier algorithms.

